# Machine Learning 101 for Scientists
## What is machine learning, and how is it used in science?
Machine learning is a field which attempts to use data with statistical and mathematical models to either learn complex patterns in the data or make predictions on unseen data. For scientists, this means that complicated tasks can be semi-automated. [DeepLabCut](https://www.mackenziemathislab.org/deeplabcut) and [SLEAP](https://sleap.ai/) are great examples of this, since they make animal pose tracking *much* faster.

    <img src="https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/57f6d51c9f74566f55ecf271/1665060903598-UK6UI28ND04D6OPLXKSG/ezgif.com-gif-maker%2B%289%29.gif?format=750w" class="grid-w33" />
{{< /gallery >}}

Other methods can help scientists find complex patterns in data that would otherwise be challenging or impossible to discover. Autoencoder models are a great tool for this kind of data-driven discovery, since they can identify latent (low-dimensional) representations of high-dimensional data. In particular, Latent Factor Analysis via Dynamical Systems [(LFADS)](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41592-018-0109-9) and Sparse Identification of Nonlinear Dynamics [(SINDy) Autoencoders](https://www.pnas.org/doi/full/10.1073/pnas.1906995116) have been used, respectively, to model latent brain states and recover latent dynamics from high-dimensional data. <br>

<img src="https://tikz.net/janosh/autoencoder.png" height=100, style="background-color:white;" caption="Autoencoder model">
<img src="https://snel-repo.github.io/autolfads/img/LFADS_architecture.png" height=200, style="background-color:white;" caption="LFADS model">


Machine learning is basically automated statistics, which means *you have to be careful*. Avoiding p-hacking and meeting modeling assumptions are hard in regular statistics, let alone in a high-dimensional, undersampled, and overparameterized regime. Many people think letting a computer make decisions removes bias, but if the data were made by humans, the bias will still leak in. <br>

Training a model poorly and not taking appropriate consideration to reduce bias can lead to real world harm: <br>
[Police facial recognition technology still can't tell black people apart](https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/police-facial-recognition-technology-cant-tell-black-people-apart/) <br>
[Amazon scraps secret AI recruiting tool that only recommended men](https://www.reuters.com/article/us-amazon-com-jobs-automation-insight/amazon-scraps-secret-ai-recruiting-tool-that-showed-bias-against-women-idUSKCN1MK08G/) <br>
[The discriminatory impact of credit scores](https://www.publicjustice.net/the-discriminatory-impact-of-credit-scores/) <br>
[Courts use very biased algorithms to recommend parole](https://www.propublica.org/article/how-we-analyzed-the-compas-recidivism-algorithm) <br>

### Types of machine learning

Machine learning algorithms broadly take one of a few forms (though many models blur these lines):
* **Supervised learning**: explicit examples inputs and outputs are given (i.e. the data are labeled) but the relationship between them must be learned.
* **Unsupervised learning**: this form of learning is more abstract, but generally relies on algorithms that try to uncover structure in data without giving explicit labels for training samples. For example, k-nearest neighbors just finds clusters without knowing anything else about the data structure. Similarly, autoencoders force the input down to only a few features, but has to reconstruct the input at the output stage. These models thus have to find a low-dimensional representation of the high-dimensional data to perform well.
* **Semi-supervised learning**: this form of learning is a mixture of supervised and unsupervised learning. In general, algorithms in this category have some training labels or other knowledge given to the model about the data, but not all labels are provided. This can guide the model in the correct direction and allow for discovery of complex relationships that are otherwise challenging to discover in unsupervised models or challenging to label or even know about ahead of time in supervised models.
* **Reinforcement learning**: this form of learning is formulated slightly differently than the other frameworks in that the model is controlling an agent in an environment (think of a player in a game). The agent typically tries to maximize a reward function (think the score in the game) through (potentially non-deterministic) interactions with the environment. The agent’s choices guide what happens in the environment, and the environment affects the agent. The agent has to sample different choices to learn when to make what choice. Thus, the model’s training data come from its past choices, and so the training data are changing throughout the experiment. If specific combinations of random choices are not made in the game to start making progress, the agent can never learn choices that do well (think of trying to win a game of chess with random moves – in this case, you might want the reward function to correspond to the number of pieces you have won, since you can make progress on that faster and start to move in the right direction easier than if you had to randomly win.)
* **Scientific Machine Learning**: This is the youngest form of machine learning in the group. Models in this category typically try to learn time-varying dynamics from data, so there is no labeled data, but the model has to output something usable by an ordinary differential equation solver to reconstruct the original data. In that sense, these models are closest to unsupervised learning.


### Necessities for machine learning tasks
There are 4 main components that are needed for any machine learning goal: data, a model, a way to evaluate that model's performance (commonly called a loss function), and a way to find the right parameters for that model (commonly, an optimization algorithm that finds parameters that minimize your loss).



*   **Data** for machine learning tasks can come in many forms. For example, you might use features of houses (square footage, number of bedrooms, etc.) to predict the price of a house. Or you might use an amino acid sequences to predict a protein's 3D structure!
  * Generally, machine learning models are *data hungry*, meaning that bigger datasets will yield better models.
  * Splitting your data into training and testing datasets allows you to avoid overfitting the model to specifics of your dataset.
  <img src="https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230829151403/Bias-and-Variance-in-Machine-Learning.webp" width=600>



* **Models** are essentially parametrized functions that learn a relationship between some input and some output (e.g. house square footage and house price.)
  * Models can be as simple as linear regression or as complicated as ChatGPT. Show examples of common models in ML are Decision Trees, Random Forests, Kernel Regression (SVM), Naïve Bayes, Gaussian Mixture Models, and Neural Networks.
  *	Models are generally used for prediction on new data but can also be used for studying the structure of the data itself. They're good at interpolation, not extrapolation.
  *	You must make sure the model actually has the capacity to model your data well (i.e. linear regression won't work well for most problems because most problems aren't linear.)

*	A **loss function** is a metric of how poorly the model is performing its desired goal (think \\(1-R^2\\)). We want to minimize the loss of the model.
  *	For example, on average how far off is the prediction of a house price from its square footage?
      * \\(L(y, \hat{y}) = \frac{1}{N}Σ_{i=1}^N|y - \hat{y}|\\) where \\(y\\) is the real house price, \\(\hat{y}\\) is the predicted house price, and \\(L\\) corresponds to what we call "mean squared error" between the true value and the prediction.
      * Generally, mean squared error is used rather than mean absolute error, since it is continuous and differentiable (among other reasons).
  *	Loss functions can get pretty complicated, though. 

  * The loss function you choose will depend on what type of task you are using the model for. 
      * **Regression:** a regression model (not just linear!) is generally trying to predict continuous values or vectors. The house price example is a regression model, and so would using fancy neural networks to predict stock prices. Simple regression models typically use mean squared error loss or something similar.
      * **Classification:** a classification model tries to assign each data point a pre-defined label, such as determining a handwritten digit from an image. ChatGPT is also a classification model that tries to output the most likely next word for some input from a dictionary of possible words. Typically, classification models outputs a vector of probabilities that each label is the correct classification. Simple classification models will typically use a loss called cross entropy between the output probability vector and a “one-hot” encoded vector with the true classification. Minimizing this loss simultaneously maximizes the probability of predicting the correct classification while penalizing any non-zero probabilities for all incorrect classifications. 
      * **Other:** Regression and classification are the “primary” ways to think about a model, but many machine learning algorithms do not fit into either of these categories. Depending on your goals, you might want to optimize the loss for your domain. For instance, clustering, dimensionality reduction, recommendation systems, protein folding, natural language processing, image generation, etc. are all slightly outside the traditional classification/regression split and require more nuanced approaches.
          * Further, you might want the model to behave in a certain way. Imagine you’re trying to determine if someone has Ebola: in that case, you would be fine if the accuracy of the model was sacrificed slightly to ensure that as many people who have the disease are correctly identified, even if some people who do not have the disease are incorrectly misidentified.

## Code examples

We'll be going through a lot today, and it is important to note that *you do not need to understand every aspect of the code or math*. The main goal is for you to understand the thought processes behind some ML algorithms and workflows. If you are interested in working with these models, working with their code is the easiest part of the workflow. Coming up with a sound question, dataset, goal, model, and optimization scheme are all much more challenging.

### Import modules
Before we get too far, lets import the modules that we'll need to run the code:


```julia
using Images, CSV, DataFrames # Data wrangling
using Plots, Measures, LaTeXStrings, IJulia # Plotting
using Statistics, LinearAlgebra # Basic functions (mean, std, matrix multiplication, etc.)
using ForwardDiff # Automatic differentiation
```

### Linear regression (explicit solution)
One of the simplest machine learning models is linear regression. Imagine we have a dataset of predictor variables (e.g. house size, number of bathrooms, etc.) that we'll call \\(X\\) and variables we're trying to predict (commonly, targets) that we'll call \\(Y\\). These targets might be the house price, the income of the owner, etc. Generally, we have some **training** samples, which we use to fit the parameters of the model to the data, \\(β\\). After fitting the model, we will generally have some error that we call \\(ϵ\\).

We want to model this relationship:
\\(Y = X\beta + \epsilon\\). We know the values of \\(X\\) and \\(Y\\), so we need to solve for \\(β\\). It might be tempting to just invert \\(X\\), but the inverse is only defined for square matrices, which \\(X\\) is likely not. Instead, we can first multiply both sides by the transpose \\(X\\), which ensures the product on the right side of the equals sign is square: \\(X'Y = (X'X)\hat{\beta}\\). Now that we have a square matrix on the right, we can multiply both sides by its inverse to find our estimate for \\(β\\), which we'll call \\(\hat{β}\\). Finally, we have \\(\hat{\beta} = (X'X)^{-1}X'Y\\).


```julia
X = rand(5, 5)
Y = rand(5, 5)
get_β(X, Y) = inv(X'X) * X' * Y

β = get_β(X, Y)
norm(Y .- X*β) # equivalent to sum((Y .- X*β) .^ 2)
```
    8.332719000849269e-14

This function works for square matrices, but the inverse becomes numerically unstable for non-square matrices. To fix this, we can use the pseudo-inverse instead, which is more numerically stable.


```julia
get_β_better(X, Y) = pinv(X'X) * X' * Y
X = rand(5, 6)
Y = rand(5, 12)
β = get_β(X, Y)
β_better = get_β_better(X, Y)
@show norm(Y .- X*β)
@show norm(Y .- X*β_better);
```

    norm(Y .- X * β) = 4.382940420160015
    norm(Y .- X * β_better) = 6.777333790151298e-15


In Julia and MATLAB, you can just use the `\` (backslash) operator, which will dispatch the best version for left division of matrices based on your data types.


```julia
β_backslash = X \ Y
isapprox(β_backslash, β_better)
```
    true

### Linear regression (gradient descent)

Another way that we can learn the best coefficients is using **gradient descent**. To use this method, we have to define a loss function and learnable parameters. We then take the derivative of the loss with respect to the parameters and change the parameters slightly in the direction of the negative derivative to reduce the loss. <br> For a simple regression with one dependent and one independent variable, we would define our loss as \\(L = \frac{1}{N}\Sigma_{i=1}^N(y_i - \hat{y_i})^2\\), where \\(\hat{y}\\) is the predicted value for \\(y\\) from our regression model. Thus, our loss can be expanded to \\(L = \frac{1}{N}\Sigma_{i=1}^N(y_i - (x_i\beta+b))^2\\), where \\(\beta\\) is the slope of the line, and \\(b\\) is the bias, or y-intercept. Now, we can take the derivative of our loss with resepct to our learnable parameters: <br>
$$
\frac{dL}{d\beta} = \frac{2}{N}\Sigma_{i=1}^N(-x_i[y_i - x_i\beta + b])
$$
$$
\frac{dL}{db} = \frac{-2}{N}\Sigma_{i=1}^N([y_i - x_i\beta - b])
$$
Let's create some data:


```julia
X = randn(100)
slope = 8; bias = -2; noise_std = 1.0
Y = (slope .* X .+ bias) .+ (noise_std .* randn(size(X)...))
scatter(X, Y, legend=:false, xlabel="X", ylabel="Y")
```

Define our derivatives:


```julia
dL_dβ(X, Y, β, b) = (2/length(X))*(sum([-x*(y-x*β-b) for (x, y) in zip(X, Y)]))
dL_db(X, Y, β, b) = (-2/length(X))*(sum([y-x*β-b for (x,y) in zip(X, Y)]))
```




    dL_db (generic function with 1 method)



If we evaluate the derivatives of the loss function with respect to each parameter, you can see that they intersect the x-axis at roughly the true value.


```julia
plot(-10:0.1:10, [dL_dβ(X, Y, x, bias) for x in -10:0.1:10], label=L"$\frac{dL}{d\beta}$", ylabel="dL")
plot!(-10:0.1:10, [dL_db(X, Y, slope, x) for x in -10:0.1:10], label=L"$\frac{dL}{db}$")
hline!([0.0], label=L"Y = 0")
vline!([bias], label=L"X = %$bias")
vline!([slope], label=L"X = %$slope")
```

Generally, we will take the derivatives and use them to adjust our parameters iteratively with a small learning rate. We want to minimize the loss, so we will take steps in the direction of the *negative* derivative.


```julia
iterations = 75
learning_rate = .5
β, b = randn(2)
scatter(X, Y)
min_X, max_X = extrema(X)
for itr in 1:iterations
    IJulia.clear_output(true)
    dL_dβ_current = dL_dβ(X, Y, β, b)
    dL_db_current = dL_db(X, Y, β, b)

    β -= learning_rate * dL_dβ_current
    b -= learning_rate * dL_db_current

    X_test = min_X:0.2:max_X
    scatter(X, Y, label="Data")
    p1 = plot!(X_test, X_test .* β .+ b, label="Current Estimate")
    display(p1)
    sleep(0.1)
end
β, b
```

A quick note: while it is easy to define the derivatives with respect to our parameters for such a simple model, these gradients can get out of hand for more complex systems. One way to overcome this limitation is to use Automatic Differentiation, which can automatically calculate the derivative of an arbitrary function for a given input.


```julia
f(x::Vector) = sum(1/3 .* x .^3)
# Now we can make a function that takes the
# gradient of the function f with respect to x
g = x -> ForwardDiff.gradient(f, x)

println("Gradient: ", g([1, 3, 5])) # Gradient will be x^2
```

    Gradient: [1.0, 9.0, 25.0]


Automatic differentiation can handle complex cases, like `for` loops and `if` statements


```julia
function f(x::Vector)
   k = length(x)
   ans = 0.0
   for i in 1:k
      if x[i] > 0.0
         ans = ans + x[i]
      else
         ans = ans - x[i]
      end
   end
   return(ans)
end

g = x -> ForwardDiff.gradient(f, x)

println("Gradient = ", g([-1.0, 1.0, 2.0, -2.0])) # Should just be sign(x)
```

    Gradient = [-1.0, 1.0, 1.0, -1.0]


### Decision Tree

A decision tree model functions by splitting the data into binary groups based on the values of specific features. Each split happens at tree nodes, and the resulting classification label or regressed value is contained in the leaf node. \
Optimal split values are determined by calculating the *entropy* of the resulting data with respect to the target variable. Entropy is a challenging (and deep!) concept, but the easiest description for us is uncertainty. We typically measure entropy in units of information (e.g. bits) which is a good unit for us because it represents how many binary splits (*questions we ask*) would be needed to uniquely identify a sample. A good model will maximize the entropy of the outcome distribution at every split, because this reduces the entropy (uncertainty) maximally after each split (question).

Here's an example decision tree based on the Iris flower classification dataset:
<img src="https://scikit-learn.org/stable/_images/iris.svg" width=500>

This model is trying to classify flowers into one of three categories based on simple features about the flowers. The most informative way to split the data is by whether the `petal_length` variable is less than or equal to 2.45cm. This split cleanly divides the data into two groups:50 samples of just `setosa` flowers, and 100 samples of `virginica` and `versicolor` flowers. The next optimal split divides the two groups nearly evenly, with 49 `versicolor` flowers and 5 `virginica` flowers in one group, while only 1 `versicolor` flower and 45 `virginica` flowers in the other group.

The remaining splits in the tree are used to distinguish the final few data points. If you fit the tree until every sample is perfectly classified, though, your model will likely be overfit to your training data and will not generalize well. Decision trees and random forests have several options for reducing overfitting, though.

The entropy of a distribution of probabilities is defined as \\((\vec{p})=\Sigma_{i=1}^N[-p_i*\log(p_i)]\\). Let's write a function that can calculate the entropy for a vector input.


```julia
H(p::Float64) = -p*log2(p)
H(p::Vector{Float64}) = sum(H.(p))
```

```julia
# Function to load the image
function load_image(image_path, edge_size)
    img = load(image_path)
    return img[edge_size:end-round(Int64, edge_size / 2), edge_size:end-edge_size]
end

# Function to cut the image into a grid and store each section
function cut_and_store_sections(image, edge_size)
    card_array = []
    img_height, img_width = size(image)

    # Calculate the section height and width
    section_height = div(img_height, 3)
    section_width = div(img_width, 8)

    # Iterate over each row and column to cut and save each section
    for row in 1:3
        for col in 1:8
            # Calculate the coordinates of the section
            start_row = (row - 1) * section_height + 1
            end_row = min(row * section_height, img_height)
            start_col = (col - 1) * section_width + 1
            end_col = min(col * section_width, img_width)

            # Extract the section
            section = image[start_row:end_row, start_col:end_col]

            push!(card_array, section[edge_size:end-edge_size, edge_size:end-edge_size])
        end
    end
    return card_array
end

# Get indices from the DataFrame where the given feature is and is not true
function get_indices(df, feature)
    have_feature_indices = findall(df[:, feature] .== 1)
    dont_have_feature_indices = findall(df[:, feature] .== 0)
    return have_feature_indices, dont_have_feature_indices
end

# Find the card for a name and show it
function show_card(name)
    ind = findall(df.Name .== name)[1]
    display(card_array[ind])
end

# Show all the cards that have a given feature and all the cards that don't
function show_groups(df, feature)
    have_inds, dont_have_inds = get_indices(df, feature)
    println("Characters with $feature == true")
    p1 = mosaicview(card_array[have_inds]..., ncol=8, npad=5, rowmajor=true, fillvalue=0.2)
    display(p1)
    println("Characters with $feature == false")
    p2 = mosaicview(card_array[dont_have_inds]..., ncol=8, npad=5, rowmajor=true, fillvalue=0.2)
    display(p2)
end
```

```julia
# Write a function that gets the entropy of one feature
function get_feature_entropy(df, feature)
    have_inds, dont_have_inds = get_indices(df, feature)

    n_have = length(have_inds)
    n_dont_have = length(dont_have_inds)
    probability_have = n_have / (n_have + n_dont_have)
    probability_dont_have = 1.0 - probability_have
    return H([probability_have, probability_dont_have])
end
```

We're going to write our own simple decision tree function that loops through our data, finds the best variable to use to split the data, and uses the iteratively to build the tree. \
First we need to define a `Node` in the tree, which will hold the feature name that will be used to split the data, and will link to the nodes "beneath" it in the tree so we can traverse the tree later.


```julia
mutable struct Node
    feature::Union{String, Nothing}
    yes_node::Union{Node, Nothing}
    no_node::Union{Node, Nothing}
end

# Overload the Base.show function to customize the printing of Node objects
function Base.show(io::IO, node::Node)
    print_node(io, node, 0, "Root Node's")
end

# Define a helper function to recursively print the tree structure
function print_node(io::IO, node::Union{Node, Nothing}, indent::Int, mode::String)
    if node == nothing
        return
    end

    # Print the current node with indentation
    println(io, "  " ^ indent, "$mode Feature: ", node.feature)

    # Print the left subtree
    print_node(io, node.no_node, indent + 1, "No Node's")

    # Print the right subtree
    print_node(io, node.yes_node, indent + 1, "Yes Node's")
end
```

    print_node (generic function with 1 method)

```julia
# Initialize our Decision Tree with a root node that splits based on the best feature
best_feature = feature_names[argmax(entropies[.!(isnan.(entropies))])]
root = Node(best_feature, nothing, nothing)
```

    Root Node's Feature: is_woman

Now, we're going to use recursion on this root node to build the rest of the tree. Again, the code and math isn't very important here. What's most important is that you understand that each time we add a node (and split the data), we want to do it as optimally as possible to separate out the remaining individuals the best.


```julia
function update_root!(root, df)
    # Base case for recursion when no people left in DataFrame
    if size(df)[1] == 0
        return
    end

    yes_inds, no_inds = get_indices(df, root.feature)

    df_yes = df[yes_inds, :]
    yes_entropies = get_feature_entropy(df_yes)

    # Remove NaNs (created when we recurse since there are no samples for some features)
    feature_names = names(df_yes)[.!(isnan.(yes_entropies))]
    yes_entropies = yes_entropies[.!(isnan.(yes_entropies))]
    if length(yes_entropies) > 0
        # Set the next node's best feature and recursively call this function on the yes_node
        root.yes_node = Node(nothing, nothing, nothing)
        root.yes_node.feature = feature_names[argmax(yes_entropies)]
        update_root!(root.yes_node, df_yes)
    end

    df_no = df[no_inds, :]
    no_entropies = get_feature_entropy(df_no)

    # Remove NaNs (created when we recurse since there are no samples for some features)
    feature_names = names(df_no)[.!(isnan.(no_entropies))]
    no_entropies = no_entropies[.!(isnan.(no_entropies))]
    if length(no_entropies) > 0
        root.no_node = Node(nothing, nothing, nothing)
        root.no_node.feature = feature_names[argmax(no_entropies)]
        update_root!(root.no_node, df_no)
    end

end
```




    update_root! (generic function with 1 method)

Now, let's evaluate how well our model really did. Let's write a function called `traverse_tree` that takes the tree and a name, and follows the tree until the individual is uniquely identified.


```julia
function traverse_tree!(root, name, path)
    if root == nothing
        return
    end
    df_name = df[df.Name .== name, :]
    has_feature = df_name[1, root.feature] == 1
    if has_feature
        push!(path, (root.feature, "Yes"))
        traverse_tree!(root.yes_node, name, path)
    else
        push!(path, (root.feature, "No"))
        traverse_tree!(root.no_node, name, path)
    end
end
path = Tuple[]
traverse_tree!(root, "Mike", path)
path
```




    4-element Vector{Tuple}:
     ("is_woman", "No")
     ("has_dark_hair", "Yes")
     ("has_hat", "Yes")
     ("likes_music", "No")



Here we can see that for Mike, the tree only required 4 binary questions to uniquely identify him. Since there are 24 cards in the Guess Who deck, splitting the samples once would give 12 cards in one deck and 12 in another ([12, 12]), a second split would give [6, 6, 6, 6], a third split would give [3, 3, 3, 3, 3, 3, 3, 3], and a fourth split would give 16 decks, 8 of which have 1 card and 8 of which have 2 cards. So, 50% of the time, a 5th split will be required to uniquely identify each individual. In Mike's case, we didn't need the 5th question, but for other cards we will. Farah, for example, needs 5 questions to be uniquely identified.

There are 24 individuals in the Guess Who deck, so we are essentially optimally encoding each individual with our decision tree.

This is a fun example, but it is *just one* in-depth example of *one type* of machine learning model. There are many other models, loss functions, optimization algorithms, and even whole frameworks of machine learning we couldn't possibly cover in a short introduction like this. \
In general, for a scientific project, you would be fitting models to discover complex relationships between variables, not trying to beat a Guess Who game. Depending on the model, though, discovering the exact relationship between your variables may be tricky, so two good rules of thumb are to stick to the simplest model you need and to err on the side of model explainability over model performance.

## Next steps

* Python is the probably easiest way to get started with machine learning and deep learning. There are many tools readily available, a wide user-base with lots of support, and the syntax is beginner-friendly. R also has a lot of support for machine learning, but don’t expect the newest (or even newer) models most of the time.
* Andrew Ng and Jeremy Howard both have great full courses on machine learning!
* **SciKit Learn** is the go-to package for many scientific computing and machine learning tasks. The API is very easy to use and the documentation is very thorough. The package uses **NumPy**, a python package optimized for fast numerical computations.
* There are many options for deep learning, but the standard packages are **Tensorflow/Keras** (Google), **PyTorch** (Facebook/Meta), and **JAX** (also Google).
* You can test out your ability (and learn new tips!) by participating in **Kaggle** data science competitions. They have a ton of datasets you can practice with!
